WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:12.500
PROFESSOR: I think you
will get going.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:15.600
A lot of people are not here,
but I think if the MRS meeting

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:19.490
were going on across the river
I would be there too if I

00:00:19.490 --> 00:00:23.120
didn't have a class to go to.

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:28.560
We had last time finished
a discussion strain.

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:34.910
And we introduced strain by
defining it as a displacement,

00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:38.170
each component of a vector
displacement U as being given

00:00:38.170 --> 00:00:45.520
by a set of coefficients, eij
times x of j, which says that

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:49.000
the displacement in a deformed
body varies linearly with the

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.170
position of the particular
point in the body.

00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:55.360
We could also express the
same thing in terms

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:57.330
of change of length.

00:00:57.330 --> 00:01:01.790
The change in the vector U would
be given by-- we show

00:01:01.790 --> 00:01:03.320
the same set of coefficients--

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:07.150
eij times delta x of j.

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:09.350
So whether you want the
displacement vector or you

00:01:09.350 --> 00:01:13.450
want the fractional change of
length, you get this by an

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:17.680
expression of the same sort.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.540
We saw though that unless we
define the coefficients

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:28.800
correctly we could have a
situation where a body is not

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:32.900
only deformed but is
rotated as well.

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.020
And we saw that in general
unless we define these

00:01:37.020 --> 00:01:43.420
coefficients carefully we would
include in this tensor a

00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:46.740
component of pure rotation,
rigid body rotation.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:50.070
And this would not measure
deformation.

00:01:50.070 --> 00:01:53.470
However, regardless of its
suitability or unsuitability,

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:57.060
the positional vector
is a vector.

00:01:57.060 --> 00:01:59.280
It transforms like a vector.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:03.660
The displacement U is a vector,
and it will transform

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:09.810
like a vector; ergo, the 3 by
3 array eij is a second-rank

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:13.140
tensor and we'll transform
like a tensor.

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:20.310
We showed though that we could
take eij and get rid of the

00:02:20.310 --> 00:02:24.000
pure rotation that might
be contained in those

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.840
coefficients by writing it as
a tensor epsilon ij plus

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:34.210
another tensor omega ij.

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:37.890
And that was a new wrinkle,
the concept of adding two

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:41.460
tensors together to get
a third tensor.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:43.980
We did run into that before.

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:48.500
And we define the elements of
the two tensors epsilon and

00:02:48.500 --> 00:03:00.580
omega; epsilon ij was given by
one half of eij plus eji, and

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:07.750
omega ij is given by one
half of omega ij.

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:10.810
And notice the order of the
subscripts here in this

00:03:10.810 --> 00:03:11.420
difference.

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:15.580
That is a matter of definition,
but it defines

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:19.250
which term is omega ij
and which is omega

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:21.670
ji minus omega ji.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:24.590
I'm sorry.

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:28.970
This should be eij minus eji.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:35.430
And we showed that at a tensor
of this form which would have

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:50.220
all of the diagonal terms zero
and the off-diagonal terms

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:56.540
equal to the negative of one
another that a tensor of this

00:03:56.540 --> 00:04:07.210
form does indeed correspond
to pure body rotation.

00:04:07.210 --> 00:04:10.230
We showed that by looking at
a point at the end of a

00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:17.320
positional vector U and looked
at a displacement which would

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.610
be exactly at right
angles to it.

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:28.030
And the U would be given
by the tensor relation.

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:36.070
We showed that U dot r is
identically zero when the

00:04:36.070 --> 00:04:43.940
displacement vector is given by
this tensor with diagonal

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:47.080
term zero and the off-diagonal
terms equal to the negative of

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:48.540
one another.

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:54.170
So we have then from a general
tensor of the form eij

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:59.080
constructed in the terms epsilon
ij something that is a

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.230
measure of true deformation.

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:05.750
It is a symmetric tensor
by definition.

00:05:05.750 --> 00:05:08.950
And therefore in addition to all
of the other properties of

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:15.770
second-rank tensor, namely
having a law of transformation

00:05:15.770 --> 00:05:19.140
and staying symmetric for any
arbitrary change of coordinate

00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:28.480
systems, the radius normal
property also works.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.670
Hence, the representation
surface that we construct from

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:40.980
the tensor epsilon ij xi
xj equals 1, gives

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:42.345
us the strain quadric.

00:05:47.430 --> 00:05:53.906
And it has the property that the
radius gives us the value

00:05:53.906 --> 00:06:01.825
of strain in a given
direction.

00:06:07.550 --> 00:06:12.430
And the value of the radius
literally is going to be the

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:18.390
vector that's on the left hand
side, the magnitude of U times

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:23.500
the component of U that is
parallel to the radial vector

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:25.300
per unit radial vector.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:33.170
And this then is the tensile
strain, the fractional change

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:40.050
of length as we look
in this direction.

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:46.530
The radius normal is going to
give us the direction of the

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:53.780
total displacement U. And the
value of the property in that

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:58.490
direction is going to be the
product of that displacement

00:06:58.490 --> 00:07:01.940
with a unit vector in the
direction of interest.

00:07:01.940 --> 00:07:04.850
And therefore that is the
tensile strain as we said

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:07.220
before from the general
properties of the quadric.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:14.600
So everything we said about
second-rank tensor and in

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:21.920
particular symmetric tensor
holds for the strain tensor.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:31.990
We can talk about diagonalizing
the strain

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:36.290
tensor into a form epsilon 1,
1, epsilon 22, zero zero,

00:07:36.290 --> 00:07:37.920
epsilon 33.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.950
And I'll remind you that we know
how to do this to set up

00:07:40.950 --> 00:07:45.120
the normal equations and solve
for the eigenvalues and then

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:49.100
look for the principal
axes of a tensor.

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:54.180
There are special forms
of the strain tensor.

00:07:54.180 --> 00:07:58.890
Something that 1 diagonal
goes into this form is

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:00.245
called plane strain.

00:08:04.989 --> 00:08:09.610
And I love the melodic nature
of that, the plane strain.

00:08:09.610 --> 00:08:13.640
If this were strain induced by
a Modernistic transformation,

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:16.990
we could call it the
Bain plane strain.

00:08:16.990 --> 00:08:19.120
If we diagonalized it,
it would be the

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:21.830
main Bain plane strains.

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:26.150
And if that deformation took
place in an aircraft window,

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:31.740
we could call it the plane-pane
main Bain strains.

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:34.630
And we could continue on
indefinitely, but I think

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:37.270
you're finding this tiresome.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:42.590
Another form of the strain
tensor that doesn't look what

00:08:42.590 --> 00:08:48.190
it actually represents is
epsilon 1 zero minus epsilon 1

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:50.170
zero zero zero zero.

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.990
That looks peculiar,
very special.

00:08:56.990 --> 00:09:00.870
But, again, this is analogous
to what we found for stress.

00:09:00.870 --> 00:09:08.860
If we rotate this tensor 45
degrees, we would find that

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:12.070
treat tensor was diagonally,
had all the

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:13.700
diagonal elements zero.

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:21.600
And we would have the
epsilon 11 prime--

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:22.940
let's just call it
epsilon prime--

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:25.940
and this epsilon prime
zero zero zero.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:36.100
And this is pure shear

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:42.000
Something that we'll show
shortly, and in fact I left it

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.680
to you as a problem
on a problems set.

00:09:45.680 --> 00:09:49.910
The sum of the diagonal
elements, epsilon 11 plus

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:57.070
epsilon 22 plus epsilon 33 is
something that's defined as

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:58.550
the trace of the tensor.

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:09.950
And for the strain tensor, the
trace turns out to be equal to

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:14.730
delta V over the fractional
change in volume.

00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:18.070
And we'll show that in just
a little bit as well.

00:10:18.070 --> 00:10:23.960
So a characteristic of pure
shear is that it does not

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:26.660
result in any change of
volume of the solid.

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:29.710
There's deformation, but the
volume stays exactly the same.

00:10:57.030 --> 00:11:00.370
Let me then proceed to show that
the trace of the strain

00:11:00.370 --> 00:11:04.180
tensor is indeed the
change in volume.

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:19.530
And want I'll do is to look at
an element of volume that is

00:11:19.530 --> 00:11:24.810
oriented along the principal
elements of strain.

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:30.970
So if this as x1, this is x2,
and this is x3, the strain

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:32.690
tensor I'll assume
is oriented.

00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:36.716
So we have a term epsilon 11
zero zero zero zero; epsilon

00:11:36.716 --> 00:11:42.560
22 zero zero zero; epsilon 33.

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:50.500
So let's suppose that the solid
originally has edges L1,

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:54.590
L2, and L3 along x1, x2,
and x3, respectively.

00:11:54.590 --> 00:11:58.040
So the initial volume before any
deformation will be simply

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:01.020
L1 times L2 times L3.

00:12:06.157 --> 00:12:10.260
Let's suppose now we impose
the strain, and the volume

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:14.090
then we'll increase to some
value of V plus delta V. And

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:19.270
the length L1 will change
to a value L1 times 1

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:21.870
plus epsilon 11.

00:12:21.870 --> 00:12:25.480
That is to say it'll be L1
plus epsilon 11 times L1,

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:28.000
which can be factored
out in this fashion.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:33.240
L2 changes to L2 times
1 plus epsilon 22.

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:41.660
And L3 changes to L3 plus
epsilon 33 times L3, which

00:12:41.660 --> 00:12:44.250
I'll write in this fashion.

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:50.480
So expanding this product,
it'll be L1, L2, L3.

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:54.930
And then if I simply multiply
out these terms, I'll have 1,

00:12:54.930 --> 00:13:02.650
and then I'll have epsilon 11
plus epsilon 22 plus epsilon

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:06.140
11 times epsilon 22.

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:10.370
And this will be times
1 plus epsilon 33.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:15.330
And if I carry out that
multiplication,

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:18.140
that will be 1 plus--

00:13:18.140 --> 00:13:25.470
and I'll get exactly these terms
again-- epsilon 11 plus

00:13:25.470 --> 00:13:34.110
epsilon 22 plus epsilon
11 times epsilon 22.

00:13:34.110 --> 00:13:41.700
And then a term epsilon 33 plus
epsilon 11 epsilon 33

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:46.440
plus epsilon 22 times
epsilon 33.

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:51.685
And then a third-order term,
epsilon 11 times epsilon 22

00:13:51.685 --> 00:13:54.860
times epsilon 33.

00:13:54.860 --> 00:13:58.360
Now having gone through the
painful process of expanding

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:03.160
that, I will proceed to say that
the epsilons are always

00:14:03.160 --> 00:14:05.470
going to be very small.

00:14:05.470 --> 00:14:08.180
Elastic strains are typically
on the order of 10

00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:09.780
to the minus 6.

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:14.020
So a product of two of those
strains is 10 to the minus 12.

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:16.360
And a product of three of those
terms is going to be on

00:14:16.360 --> 00:14:21.260
the order of 10 to
the minus 18.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:23.770
So this last term is going
to be minuscule.

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:30.120
And now I use a higher order
term intentionally rather than

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:31.140
a higher rank term.

00:14:31.140 --> 00:14:33.250
This is really a term
of higher order.

00:14:33.250 --> 00:14:38.170
The same is true of all the
peer-wise projects of this

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:39.180
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:43.850
So I now have left if I turn out
these higher order terms

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:49.430
to pasture, I'll have 1 plus
epsilon 11 plus epsilon 22

00:14:49.430 --> 00:14:51.260
plus epsilon 33.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:53.210
And the rest is negligible.

00:14:53.210 --> 00:15:01.260
And this will be the original
volume V times 1 plus epsilon

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:07.020
11 plus epsilon 22
plus epsilon 33.

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:13.390
So delta V over V, if I subtract
off V on the left,

00:15:13.390 --> 00:15:17.360
delta V over V then is simply
going to be equal to epsilon

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:23.600
11 plus epsilon 22
plus epsilon 33.

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.690
So this is indeed the fractional
change of volume,

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:31.095
and it's the trace
of epsilon ij.

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:39.090
Now, physically, you wouldn't
expect the volume to change if

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:41.360
I change my reference
axes because

00:15:41.360 --> 00:15:43.410
that's a scalar quantity.

00:15:43.410 --> 00:15:49.000
So I've shown by a hand-waving,
backdoor argument

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.880
that in fact the trace of a
tensor does stay invariant for

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:54.690
at least this particular
tensor.

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:57.220
But it's fairly straightforward
to show that

00:15:57.220 --> 00:16:01.890
for any tensor aij the trace
of the tensor is invariant

00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:04.830
when you change the
coordinate system.

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:06.260
And that's not hard to do.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:08.440
If you're clever, it takes
about three lines.

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:11.910
So I'll invite you to the
exhilaration of discovering

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:13.807
that for yourself on
a problem set.

00:16:21.770 --> 00:16:23.080
Any questions or comments?

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:37.680
All right.

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:45.030
Having defined strain as a
symmetric second-rank tensor

00:16:45.030 --> 00:16:56.740
when we factor out rigid body
rotation, we can view strain

00:16:56.740 --> 00:17:00.730
as a physical property.

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:03.230
And I think I tried to hoodwink
you last time by

00:17:03.230 --> 00:17:10.530
saying this is a property
of material.

00:17:10.530 --> 00:17:14.339
So therefore strain tensor has
to also conform to all of the

00:17:14.339 --> 00:17:17.490
symmetry restrains that
we have derived very

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:18.839
exhaustively.

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:22.839
And you said, no, no, no, no,
that can't be; I don't believe

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:29.810
that I can only give a uniform
uniaxial deformation to an

00:17:29.810 --> 00:17:30.920
orthorhombic crystal.

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:33.190
And I say, yeah, but to get the
deformation, you have to

00:17:33.190 --> 00:17:34.410
squeeze the crystal.

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:38.080
And that is going to be linked
to the deformation by the

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:41.400
elastic constants, and they
are physical properties.

00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:43.510
And that maybe makes you
think a little bit.

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:48.520
But actually even though
operationally you impose a

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:52.600
strain by imposing a stress or
by doing something else to the

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:56.490
crystal that results in a
strain, you can nevertheless

00:17:56.490 --> 00:18:00.060
pick any stimulus you
wish to achieve a

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:02.910
desired state of strain.

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:06.400
So there is no symmetry
constraint on the form of the

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:08.690
strain tensor that can result.

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:12.560
So the stain tensor then is
not a property tensor.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:15.990
It is also a field tensor
just like stress.

00:18:15.990 --> 00:18:19.600
So it can have any form we
choose to create in it.

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:28.080
So we now have the potential
of having

00:18:28.080 --> 00:18:30.770
stress as a field tensor.

00:18:36.930 --> 00:18:40.710
And we have strain as
a field tensor.

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:50.540
And within limits, we can create
strains of these two

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:53.750
field tensors of any
form that we wish.

00:18:53.750 --> 00:18:58.600
And we can now regard these as
things that we do to crystals

00:18:58.600 --> 00:19:03.500
and look at a whole range of
properties that result when

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:09.510
the generalized force is not
a vector, a tensor of first

00:19:09.510 --> 00:19:13.170
rank, but the generalized
force is a--

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:15.300
let's say-- a stress tensor.

00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:17.320
It's a generalized force
which itself is not

00:19:17.320 --> 00:19:20.950
a first rank tensor.

00:19:20.950 --> 00:19:22.460
It's a second rank tensor.

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:24.530
So we'll see a whole collection
of interesting

00:19:24.530 --> 00:19:27.850
properties that fall
into this category.

00:19:27.850 --> 00:19:31.620
But first I'd like to look at
one remaining second-rank

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:34.860
tensor property, and that
is thermal expansion.

00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:47.360
And this is a curious
second-rank tensor property,

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:49.480
and we couldn't discuss
it until we had

00:19:49.480 --> 00:19:50.800
talked about strain.

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:54.390
And let me introduce it by
one-dimensional example.

00:19:54.390 --> 00:20:02.020
Let's suppose we have a rodlike
specimen of length L.

00:20:02.020 --> 00:20:05.850
And let's suppose it is
in equilibrium at some

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:11.850
temperature T. And then we heat
it up to some temperature

00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:14.910
T plus delta T.

00:20:14.910 --> 00:20:19.430
In response to that particular
change in temperature, the

00:20:19.430 --> 00:20:25.743
length of the rod will increase
to a length L plus

00:20:25.743 --> 00:20:28.710
delta L. It expands.

00:20:28.710 --> 00:20:32.390
And we would find experimentally
that delta L,

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:36.680
first of all, is proportional
to L. If you make the rod

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:40.010
twice as long, the amount of
expansion in an absolute sense

00:20:40.010 --> 00:20:41.810
is twice as large.

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:48.110
And secondly, provided you're
well above very, very low

00:20:48.110 --> 00:20:51.210
temperatures, close to absolute
zero, delta L will

00:20:51.210 --> 00:20:54.935
also be proportional to the
change in temperature.

00:21:00.830 --> 00:21:04.200
Thermal expansion is one of
those properties which

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:05.600
thermodynamically must
go to zero as

00:21:05.600 --> 00:21:07.330
temperature goes to zero.

00:21:07.330 --> 00:21:10.740
So the thermal expansion
coefficient that we've yet to

00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:15.450
define will be a function of
temperature as we get down to

00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:20.400
very low temperatures on the
order of a few degrees Kelvin.

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:24.140
So we can define then the
linear thermal expansion

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:37.570
coefficient for this rod as 1
over L, delta L over delta T.

00:21:37.570 --> 00:21:43.180
So this is something that will
give us the fractional change

00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:45.470
of lengths.

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:53.410
And what we can do now in
general is to say that if we

00:21:53.410 --> 00:21:57.140
create a general strain, not
a tensile strain, we have a

00:21:57.140 --> 00:22:06.580
general strain epsilon 11 plus
epsilon 12, epsilon 13, and so

00:22:06.580 --> 00:22:10.740
on, has to be symmetric.

00:22:10.740 --> 00:22:13.840
So epsilon 21 is equal
to epsilon 12.

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:28.690
We'll say that this tensor
epsilon ij will be written in

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:34.140
general for the
three-dimensional case as a

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:45.850
second-rank tensor aij times
a scalar quantity delta T.

00:22:45.850 --> 00:22:47.700
The strain is the
field tensor.

00:22:47.700 --> 00:22:48.980
That's the response.

00:22:48.980 --> 00:22:52.460
The stimulus that creates this
response is an incremental

00:22:52.460 --> 00:22:53.930
change in temperature.

00:22:53.930 --> 00:22:59.380
But as this is a second-rank
tensor and this is a scalar,

00:22:59.380 --> 00:23:02.370
an array of coefficients in
which we multiply every

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:06.200
element of a tensor by a scalar
is also a tensor.

00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:07.950
So this is called the
linear thermal

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:09.530
expansion coefficient tensor.

00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:36.100
And it is a symmetric tensor by
definition since a measure

00:23:36.100 --> 00:23:42.160
of true strain is by definition
a symmetric tensor.

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:45.490
So this is the linear thermal
expansion coefficient tensor.

