00:27:54.870 --> 00:27:58.350
ferrites for example, 7.6.

00:27:58.350 --> 00:28:01.550
Silicon carbide, a
very refractory

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:07.635
covalent compound, 4.7.

00:28:07.635 --> 00:28:12.980
For glasses, here's
a surprise.

00:28:12.980 --> 00:28:16.120
You might think that a glass
might have about the same

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:20.010
linear expansion coefficient as
the crystalline form of the

00:28:20.010 --> 00:28:21.610
same composition.

00:28:21.610 --> 00:28:30.520
But a sodium calcium silicon
oxide glass, so called

00:28:30.520 --> 00:28:34.840
soda-lime silicate glass,
is 9, fairly low.

00:28:34.840 --> 00:28:44.640
A borosilicate glass, like the
Vicor that we love to make

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:48.620
glass apparatus out of, 4.5.

00:28:48.620 --> 00:28:56.210
And one of the near record
holder is fused silica,

00:28:56.210 --> 00:29:01.920
silicio glass, and here
a measly value of 0.5.

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:06.630
So glasses have very low linear
thermal expansion

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:10.970
coefficients compared to
crystallize materials that are

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:12.790
predominantly ionic.

00:29:12.790 --> 00:29:15.830
And the reason lies in the
nature of the structure.

00:29:15.830 --> 00:29:19.790
Something like MgO has ordered
ions, and when you heat it up,

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:22.280
it expands isotropically.

00:29:22.280 --> 00:29:26.770
A glass is this random network
of edge-shared polyhedra.

00:29:26.770 --> 00:29:30.210
So when you heat it up, yes,
the dimensions of the

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:33.290
polyhedra increase in proportion
to the change of

00:29:33.290 --> 00:29:34.150
temperature.

00:29:34.150 --> 00:29:38.450
But the framework because it's
so meandering and open can

00:29:38.450 --> 00:29:42.080
buckle to accommodate the
increased size of the

00:29:42.080 --> 00:29:44.240
tetrahedra that are
in the linkage.

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:47.060
So the result is the network
buckles, but the overall

00:29:47.060 --> 00:29:52.050
microscopic thermal expansion
is very, very slight even

00:29:52.050 --> 00:29:56.030
though the tetrahedra are
changing dimensions in the

00:29:56.030 --> 00:30:00.190
same degree that they are in
these crystalline inorganic

00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:01.440
nonmetallic materials.

00:30:06.310 --> 00:30:10.360
Let me give you a handout not
that it's up to date, but

00:30:10.360 --> 00:30:15.030
there was a very nice,
convenient one-page article in

00:30:15.030 --> 00:30:18.610
the Journal of the American
Ceramic Society a number of

00:30:18.610 --> 00:30:22.330
years ago that lists thermal
