00:30:22.330 --> 00:30:24.650
expansion oxides.

00:30:24.650 --> 00:30:27.260
So let me pass that around
and let you take off

00:30:27.260 --> 00:30:28.460
for copy with that.

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:30.975
And that gives some examples of
the value of this property

00:30:30.975 --> 00:30:35.450
for, again, for polycrystalline
materials,

00:30:35.450 --> 00:30:38.130
which if you looked at a single
crystal would show

00:30:38.130 --> 00:30:40.350
anisotropy.

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:44.100
And here you'll find a few
materials in the list near the

00:30:44.100 --> 00:30:47.470
top they're arranged in order
of increasing linear thermal

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:53.090
expansion, you'll find some that
are just about zero when

00:30:53.090 --> 00:30:55.830
you have a polycrystalline
form of the material.

00:30:55.830 --> 00:31:01.160
And you'll have some that have
this very unusual behavior

00:31:01.160 --> 00:31:03.920
where the linear thermal
expansion coefficient is

00:31:03.920 --> 00:31:05.200
actually negative.

00:31:05.200 --> 00:31:06.950
So let me pass this around
for reference.

00:31:12.570 --> 00:31:17.980
Now this may seem to be a
curiosity that you can fine

00:31:17.980 --> 00:31:21.330
for a polycrystalline material
for which the individual

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:27.410
grains expand anisotropically
a bulk linear thermal

00:31:27.410 --> 00:31:31.290
expansion coefficient of zero.

00:31:31.290 --> 00:31:34.920
Why should one care other than
that being a curious result?

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:36.170
Can anybody guess?

00:31:39.272 --> 00:31:40.700
AUDIENCE: Can you
say that again?

00:31:40.700 --> 00:31:45.090
PROFESSOR: That these are
materials which in a

00:31:45.090 --> 00:31:48.650
polycrystalline form with random
grain orientation have

00:31:48.650 --> 00:31:51.840
a linear thermal expansion
coefficient this is

00:31:51.840 --> 00:31:53.090
essentially zero?

00:31:55.960 --> 00:31:58.410
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:31:58.410 --> 00:31:59.390
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:31:59.390 --> 00:32:00.380
Exactly.

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:07.120
The materials out of which you
build furnace linings and

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:11.110
tanks for melting glass or
smelting steel have to be made

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:12.690
out of polycrystalline
materials.

00:32:12.690 --> 00:32:15.680
You can't have a monolithic
single crystal that's large

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:17.330
enough to melt a significant
amount of

00:32:17.330 --> 00:32:19.070
glass in for example.

00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:23.110
And being polycrystalline, when
the material expands,

00:32:23.110 --> 00:32:27.820
there is a great deal of stress
between neighboring

00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:30.530
grains because they're
randomly oriented.

00:32:30.530 --> 00:32:35.400
If the bulk microscopic thermal
expansion coefficient

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:38.760
is zero, that is going to be
refractory that is very, very

00:32:38.760 --> 00:32:40.630
resistant to thermal shock.

00:32:40.630 --> 00:32:45.430
When you heat it up, you don't
find intergranular cracking.

00:32:45.430 --> 00:32:55.040
So the materials that have
essentially zero spatially

00:32:55.040 --> 00:32:57.910
average thermal expansion
coefficients are very

00:32:57.910 --> 00:32:59.620
attractive for refractories.

00:32:59.620 --> 00:33:03.260
You can pick up any issue
of the Journal of

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:04.580
the American Ceramics--

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:06.360
not the journal, but the
Bulletin of the American

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:12.120
Ceramic Society and you will
find refractory companies

00:33:12.120 --> 00:33:16.700
hustling materials like
Cordierite, which is a

00:33:16.700 --> 00:33:21.710
silicate material that on
average has one positive

00:33:21.710 --> 00:33:24.490
thermal expansion coefficient,
one negative thermal expansion

00:33:24.490 --> 00:33:25.350
coefficient.

00:33:25.350 --> 00:33:27.810
And the volume change of the
individual grains is

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:29.380
essentially zero.

00:33:29.380 --> 00:33:36.385
So that makes a dandy material
for refractories.

00:33:42.030 --> 00:33:47.210
Cordierite has another
interesting property that is a

00:33:47.210 --> 00:33:49.825
really nice example
of anisotropy

00:33:49.825 --> 00:33:53.340
of a physical property.

00:33:53.340 --> 00:33:55.995
If I ask you to rattle off some
properties which you know

00:33:55.995 --> 00:33:59.230
to be very anisotropic, one of
them that you wouldn't think

00:33:59.230 --> 00:34:02.600
of is color.

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:05.470
Your t-shirt is pink,
so how can that be

00:34:05.470 --> 00:34:06.790
a function of direction?

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:09.460
Well your t-shirt is not
a single crystal.

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:11.920
And their single crystals which
if you hold them up to

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:17.760
light and pass through a plain
polarized beam of light the

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:21.210
crystal has a very different
color for one direction of

00:34:21.210 --> 00:34:23.360
polarization then another.

00:34:23.360 --> 00:34:26.580
And these colors, interestingly,
very often are

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:28.630
strikingly different.

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:32.690
They're crystals that are green
in light polarized in

00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:36.670
one direction and red for
light polarized in the

00:34:36.670 --> 00:34:38.679
opposite direction.

00:34:38.679 --> 00:34:44.969
And there is in the old
Icelandic sagas--

00:34:44.969 --> 00:34:46.310
few people have heard of them.

00:34:46.310 --> 00:34:52.460
The Icelandic sagas which were
written in about the year 500

00:34:52.460 --> 00:34:56.550
are one of the early forms of
Western literature that is

00:34:56.550 --> 00:35:00.730
really great, enduring
world-class literature.

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:05.310
In the sagas, there's one
episode where Thor is sleeping

00:35:05.310 --> 00:35:09.820
and Olaf comes along and
steals his sunstone.

00:35:09.820 --> 00:35:13.690
And Thor is upset he takes
his battle as and cut

00:35:13.690 --> 00:35:15.880
Olaf's head in twain.

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:18.240
And people puzzled
for hundreds of

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:20.010
years, what is sunstone.

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:26.080
This doesn't compute
in today's age.

00:35:26.080 --> 00:35:29.950
And finally a Norwegian
archaeologist came up with a

00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:36.240
hypothesis that in Iceland there
are remarkably large and

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:41.920
remarkably transparent and
perfect single crystals of

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:43.420
Cordierite.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:46.920
And Cordierite is strikingly
pleochroic.

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:49.800
That's color that is a function
of direction.

00:35:49.800 --> 00:35:54.770
And what this archaeologist
theorized is that the Vikings

00:35:54.770 --> 00:35:59.670
would take a sunstone when they
went sailing on the North

00:35:59.670 --> 00:36:04.120
Sea, which is notoriously damp
and overcast and gray, and

00:36:04.120 --> 00:36:07.050
your principal means of
navigation was the sun.

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:09.890
But when the sky was overcast,
you couldn't see the sun.

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:13.290
But the sun as it comes through
the cloud gives you

00:36:13.290 --> 00:36:15.890
light that's very strongly
polarized.

00:36:15.890 --> 00:36:20.460
So the theory is that the
Vikings would have very

00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:23.560
perfect crystals of transparent
Cordierite, would

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:28.340
hold them up to the sky, and
turn them around until the

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:33.100
Cordierite crystal lit up a
bright, golden sunny yellow.

00:36:33.100 --> 00:36:35.020
What better name for
the sunstone.

00:36:35.020 --> 00:36:38.310
You found the sun from the
direction of polarization of

00:36:38.310 --> 00:36:40.950
the light scattered from the
cloud when you've got the

00:36:40.950 --> 00:36:42.800
crystal oriented just so.

00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:46.180
In a different orientation, it
would look murkier, look sort

00:36:46.180 --> 00:36:49.940
of a bluish purple for the other
principal direction of

00:36:49.940 --> 00:36:51.560
the birefringence.

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:57.180
So there is putting crystal
anisotropy hundreds of years

00:36:57.180 --> 00:37:02.390
ago to a very useful purpose
to navigate on cloudy days.

00:37:02.390 --> 00:37:04.810
Unfortunately, the Vikings
used it to sail down the

00:37:04.810 --> 00:37:07.750
British coast and sacked
the next village.

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:12.590
So it shows you that even the
most simple of science can be

00:37:12.590 --> 00:37:16.460
put to application
in war research.

00:37:16.460 --> 00:37:19.300
Anyway, won't go
there anymore.

00:37:19.300 --> 00:37:23.870
So index of refraction and color
can also be a strong

00:37:23.870 --> 00:37:32.040
function of direction

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:38.540
The numbers that I put on the
blackboard suggest that the

00:37:38.540 --> 00:37:43.390
magnitude of thermal expansion
coefficients are influenced

00:37:43.390 --> 00:37:47.060
very strongly by the strength
of the interatomic bonding.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:50.420
And this shows up in a very,
very striking way if you group

00:37:50.420 --> 00:37:56.810
together classes of comparable
materials.

00:37:56.810 --> 00:38:01.190
And if you plot the value of the
linear thermal expansion

00:38:01.190 --> 00:38:08.100
coefficient in units of 10 to
the minus 6 per degree C as a

00:38:08.100 --> 00:38:14.510
function of the melting point in
degrees Kelvin, the numbers

00:38:14.510 --> 00:38:20.390
range from about 400 K for
materials like sulfur up to

00:38:20.390 --> 00:38:24.160
about 3,700 for tungsten.

00:38:24.160 --> 00:38:28.120
And the variation is
so beautiful it

00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:30.690
could make you cry.

00:38:30.690 --> 00:38:34.330
It goes as the inverse
of the melting point.

00:38:34.330 --> 00:38:40.500
And way up here are materials
like for sulfur and lithium.

00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:44.420
And the way out here are
materials like tungsten.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:50.500
And their relation is given
by a equals 0.020 over the

00:38:50.500 --> 00:38:52.950
melting point in
degrees Kelvin.

00:38:57.150 --> 00:39:02.420
So very strong correlation
between melting point and

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:05.510
linear expansion for
simple elements.

00:39:05.510 --> 00:39:09.790
If you do the same thing for
compounds, you find a similar

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:15.555
parabolic relation except
it is offset.

00:39:22.450 --> 00:39:33.190
For oxides and halides, many
of them with the rock salt

00:39:33.190 --> 00:39:35.420
structure, so they
are isotropic.

00:39:35.420 --> 00:39:40.190
And again, if you plot here the
