minus 7.0 times 10 to

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:10.530
the minus 6.

00:40:17.730 --> 00:40:21.690
Finally, let me finish with some
data for single crystals

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:26.200
that provide examples
of and anisotropy.

00:40:26.200 --> 00:40:30.130
These are all hexagonal
materials.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:33.680
And I will give you the--

00:40:33.680 --> 00:40:34.600
not all hexagonal.

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:35.230
I take that back.

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:37.240
But they're all uniaxial
crystals.

00:40:37.240 --> 00:40:42.870
The value of the thermal
expansion coefficient along C

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:46.270
and the thermal expansion
coefficient that is parallel

00:40:46.270 --> 00:40:49.100
to C, so these are the elements
that would be in the

00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:53.850
diagonal isothermal
expansion tensor.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:41:00.240
So for Al2O3, which is a
hexagonal rhombohedral oxide,

00:41:00.240 --> 00:41:06.330
the two expansion coefficients
are 8.39 and 9.0 times 10 to

00:41:06.330 --> 00:41:09.840
the minus 6, not terribly
anisotropic.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:13.550
But the structure of alumina is
a close-packed arrangement

00:41:13.550 --> 00:41:18.890
of oxygen with aluminum filling
2/3 of the available

00:41:18.890 --> 00:41:20.700
octahedral holes.

00:41:20.700 --> 00:41:26.460
So it's hexagonal only because
of the sites that are filled

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:28.490
in the array.

00:41:28.490 --> 00:41:31.540
For TiO2, which is [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:31.540 --> 00:41:39.270
and therefore also uniaxial,
6.8 perpendicular to C; 8.3

00:41:39.270 --> 00:41:49.730
parallel to C. For zirconium
silicate, 3.7 and 6.2, almost

00:41:49.730 --> 00:41:51.500
a 2:1 difference.

00:41:51.500 --> 00:42:01.510
For the quartz form of silica,
which is hexagonal, 14

00:42:01.510 --> 00:42:07.550
perpendicular to C;
9 parallel to C.

00:42:07.550 --> 00:42:10.700
For carbon, the graphite form,
a layer structure--

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:17.220
you can almost guess how this
is going to turn out.

00:42:17.220 --> 00:42:21.100
It's going to be humongous
perpendicular to the lawyers

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:24.660
and very small within the plane
of these tightly bonded

00:42:24.660 --> 00:42:26.370
hexagonal nets.

00:42:26.370 --> 00:42:32.630
And that is indeed the case,
1 perpendicular to C; 27

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:38.090
parallel to C. So there is an
anisotropy of a factor of 27.

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:41.480
A few more.

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:55.220
Aluminum titanate, perpendicular
to C minus 2.6;

00:42:55.220 --> 00:43:01.636
parallel to C 11.5.

00:43:01.636 --> 00:43:06.180
A very well known example
of anisotropy, extreme

00:43:06.180 --> 00:43:09.450
anisotropy, where one principal
coefficient is

00:43:09.450 --> 00:43:14.840
positive and two are negative
is the calcite forms calcium

00:43:14.840 --> 00:43:22.100
carbonate, minus 6 and 25.

00:43:22.100 --> 00:43:26.250
For zinc metal, a hexagonal
close-packed metal, surprising

00:43:26.250 --> 00:43:30.930
degree of anisotropy,
14 and 64.

00:43:30.930 --> 00:43:37.210
And for tellurium, which is a
chain structure like selenium,

00:43:37.210 --> 00:43:44.040
27 perpendicular to C and
minus 1.6 in a direction

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:47.640
parallel to C.

00:43:47.640 --> 00:43:51.080
Even simple hexagonal
close-packed metals can do

00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:53.430
strange things at low
temperatures.

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:57.200
For zinc, the expansion
coefficients perpendicular to

00:43:57.200 --> 00:44:04.100
C and parallel to C as a
function of temperature go at

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:09.850
300 degrees C from 13 and 64.

00:44:09.850 --> 00:44:17.046
At 150, the values have
dropped to 8 and 65.

00:44:20.470 --> 00:44:26.230
At 60 degrees K perpendicular to
C, the thermal expansion is

00:44:26.230 --> 00:44:30.080
negative and has not dropped
terribly much of at all

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:34.000
parallel to C. So this is
a hexagonal close-packed

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:34.730
structure lot.

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:37.720
A lot of action and strange
things going on in the plane

00:44:37.720 --> 00:44:42.290
at the close-packed layers, but
not very much change in a

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:44.140
direction perpendicular
to the layers.

00:45:02.570 --> 00:45:05.000
Let me raise one more issue.

00:45:07.620 --> 00:45:11.600
If we were to look at some of
these strangely anisotropic

00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:15.220
materials which had negative
thermal expansion coefficients

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:19.720
in one direction and positive
in another, what would the

00:45:19.720 --> 00:45:22.810
representation quadric
look like?

00:45:22.810 --> 00:45:26.430
Suppose we looked at calcite,
for example, which has a large

00:45:26.430 --> 00:45:29.120
negative thermal expansion
coefficient.

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:32.630
And if we look at the thermal
expansion quadric when the

00:45:32.630 --> 00:45:34.840
tensor was referred
to the principal

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:40.415
axes, parallel to C--

00:45:40.415 --> 00:45:47.220
well, the thermal expansion
tensor aij along its principal

00:45:47.220 --> 00:45:53.470
axes would be along A1 in a
direction perpendicular to C,

00:45:53.470 --> 00:45:59.520
it would be for the data given
here, minus 6, zero, zero,

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:03.850
zero, minus 6, zero,
zero, zero.

00:46:03.850 --> 00:46:08.135
And A33 is 25.

00:46:10.970 --> 00:46:13.100
So that's very, very
anisotropic.

00:46:15.850 --> 00:46:17.470
But what is this going to be?

00:46:17.470 --> 00:46:21.640
This is going to be a quadric
that has the shape of an

00:46:21.640 --> 00:46:24.160
hyperboloid of two sheets.

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:26.330
So it's going to
look like this.

00:46:32.630 --> 00:46:35.650
And there'll be an asymptote
like this and then

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:37.145
asymptote like this.

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:47.330
Along the asymptote,
the radius of

00:46:47.330 --> 00:46:50.500
the quadric is infinite.

00:46:50.500 --> 00:46:55.300
So therefore along these
directions the

00:46:55.300 --> 00:47:00.670
strain is equal to zero.

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:05.140
Strain goes as 1 over
the radius squared.

00:47:10.460 --> 00:47:15.350
In this range of directions
here, the radius is imaginary.

00:47:20.300 --> 00:47:23.680
But remember that the
strain is given by 1

00:47:23.680 --> 00:47:26.220
over the radius squared.

00:47:26.220 --> 00:47:33.040
So this says that the strain is
negative, so the material

00:47:33.040 --> 00:47:35.190
has contracted.

00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:41.710
And finally, in this range of
directions where the radius is

00:47:41.710 --> 00:47:46.320
finite and positive, if the
value of strain is 1 over

00:47:46.320 --> 00:47:50.270
radius squared, this says that
the maximum deformation is

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:54.380
along the direction of the C
axis, and it's positive.

00:47:54.380 --> 00:47:57.870
The material expands along C;
the minimum radius of the

00:47:57.870 --> 00:48:02.540
quadric corresponds to the
maximum thermal expansion.

00:48:06.660 --> 00:48:09.980
So let me close with
a question.

00:48:09.980 --> 00:48:14.410
Along the asymptote of the
quadric, the strain is zero.

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:20.450
Does this mean that this
direction in a crystal of

00:48:20.450 --> 00:48:24.730
calcite does not move, no
deformation at all when you

00:48:24.730 --> 00:48:25.980
heat it up?

00:48:31.681 --> 00:48:33.669
I see faint shakes
of the head.

00:48:33.669 --> 00:48:37.148
I don't know if that's just in
awe of what's going on here or

00:48:37.148 --> 00:48:39.633
an opinion on the question.

00:48:39.633 --> 00:48:42.615
Do you think it'll
be no strain?

00:48:42.615 --> 00:48:45.100
AUDIENCE: It would
be [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:45.100 --> 00:48:46.591
PROFESSOR: Good answer.

00:48:46.591 --> 00:48:51.780
Let's remember a property of
the representation quadric.

00:48:51.780 --> 00:48:56.650
The direction of what happens
is normal to the surface of

00:48:56.650 --> 00:48:57.770
the quadric.

00:48:57.770 --> 00:49:01.420
The thing that is happening here
is the displacement; ui

00:49:01.420 --> 00:49:06.440
is given by epsilon
ij times U sub j.

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:10.260
So when we look in this
direction, the displacement,

00:49:10.260 --> 00:49:16.010
which would be normal to the
surface of the quadric, gives

00:49:16.010 --> 00:49:19.790
us this as a displacement.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:23.640
So along the asymptotes of the
quadric, you can't say that

00:49:23.640 --> 00:49:27.730
there's no deformation, but
that the deformation

00:49:27.730 --> 00:49:31.110
corresponds to pure rotation
and not any

00:49:31.110 --> 00:49:34.260
fractional change of length.

00:49:34.260 --> 00:49:37.850
In these directions, the length
changes, but it is a

00:49:37.850 --> 00:49:40.790
decrease in length within
the asymptotes.

00:49:40.790 --> 00:49:48.270
For those directions, the
strain is an extension.

00:49:48.270 --> 00:49:50.910
And again, if you want to know
the direction of the

00:49:50.910 --> 00:49:54.810
displacement, you find the
normal to the surface of the

00:49:54.810 --> 00:49:58.770
quadric in the direction of
interest, and that's the

00:49:58.770 --> 00:50:01.040
direction in which the
radius vector points.

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:09.040
All right.

00:50:09.040 --> 00:50:11.060
That's I think a good
place to quit.

00:50:15.630 --> 00:50:21.460
I think I'll say a little bit
