00:50:49.730 --> 00:50:52.780
One is to have you show for
yourself that the trace of a

00:50:52.780 --> 00:50:54.620
second-rank tensor--

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:58.210
I called it second-order
tensor--

00:50:58.210 --> 00:51:01.880
second-rank tensor the sum of
the diagonal elements is

00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:05.440
invariant for a change of
reference axes for a general

00:51:05.440 --> 00:51:08.700
direction cosine scheme for
the change of axes.

00:51:08.700 --> 00:51:12.510
And then the other two questions
are to give you some

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:17.490
practice in diagonalizing a
second-rank property tensor

00:51:17.490 --> 00:51:19.920
which is not in diagonal form.

00:51:19.920 --> 00:51:21.920
And I asked you to do
this in two ways.

00:51:21.920 --> 00:51:26.160
One is by direct solution of
the secular equation and

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:28.000
finding the eigenvectors.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.660
And then the third example,
which is for a completely

00:51:30.660 --> 00:51:33.990
general tensor, to do this by
the method of successive

00:51:33.990 --> 00:51:35.580
approximations.

00:51:35.580 --> 00:51:38.240
And you'll find after a couple
of iterations you get fairly

00:51:38.240 --> 00:51:39.630
close to convergence.

00:51:39.630 --> 00:51:42.480
So I shall pass this around.

00:51:42.480 --> 00:51:46.470
And again, I think there's
something to be

00:51:46.470 --> 00:51:47.720
learned from that.

